{
  "explanation": "The defendant committed a serious breach of trust by embezzling $25,000 from their employer, abusing their position as an accountant. However, the court must consider significant mitigating factors, notably the defendant's lack of any prior criminal record and their proactive, good faith effort to partially repay the stolen funds prior to sentencing. While the abuse of fiduciary duty requires a period of incarceration to serve as a sufficient deterrent, the non-violent nature of the crime and the partial restitution make a lengthy sentence inappropriate. A short term of incarceration, combined with subsequent probation and a strict mandate to complete full restitution, balances accountability with the opportunity for rehabilitation.",
  "verdict": 6
}
